# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: autopilot-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] An aircraft in flight is free to rotate in three dimensions: ***yaw***, nose left or right about an axis running up and down; ***pitch***, nose up or down about an axis running from wing to wing; and ***roll***, rotation about an axis running from nose to tail.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] The yaw, pitch, and roll axes are alternatively designated as *vertical*, *lateral* (or *transverse*), and *longitudinal* respectively.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] These axes move with the vehicle and rotate relative to the Earth along with the craft.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] These definitions were analogously applied to spacecraft when the first crewed spacecraft were designed in the late 1950s.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] These rotations are produced by torques (or moments) about the principal axes.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] On an aircraft, these are intentionally produced by means of moving control surfaces, which vary the distribution of the net aerodynamic force about the vehicle's center of gravity.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] Elevators (moving flaps on the horizontal tail) produce pitch, a rudder on the vertical tail produces yaw, and ailerons (flaps on the wings that move in opposing directions) produce roll.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] On a spacecraft, the movements are usually produced by a reaction control system consisting of small rocket thrusters used to apply asymmetrical thrust on the vehicle.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] Normally, these axes are represented by the letters X, Y and Z in order to compare them with some reference frame, usually named x, y, z.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] Normally, this is made in such a way that the X is used for the longitudinal axis, but there are other possibilities to do it.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] The **yaw axis** has its origin at the center of gravity and is directed towards the bottom of the aircraft, perpendicular to the wings and to the fuselage reference line.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] Motion about this axis is called **yaw**.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] A positive yawing motion moves the nose of the aircraft to the right.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] The rudder is the primary control of yaw.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] The term *yaw* was originally applied in sailing, and referred to the motion of an unsteady ship rotating about its vertical axis.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] The **pitch axis** (also called **transverse** or **lateral axis**) passes through an aircraft from wingtip to wingtip.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] Rotation about this axis is called **pitch**.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] Pitch changes the vertical direction that the aircraft's nose is pointing (a positive pitching motion raises the nose of the aircraft up and lowers the tail).
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] The elevators are the primary control surfaces for pitch.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] The **roll axis** (or **longitudinal axis**) has its origin at the center of gravity and is directed forward, parallel to the fuselage reference line.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] Motion about this axis is called **roll**.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] An angular displacement about this axis is called **bank**.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] A positive rolling motion lifts the left wing and lowers the right wing.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] The pilot rolls by increasing the lift on one wing and decreasing it on the other.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] The ailerons are the primary control of roll.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] The rudder also has a secondary effect on roll.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] These axes are related to the principal axes of inertia, but are not the same.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] They are geometrical symmetry axes, regardless of the mass distribution of the aircraft.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] In aeronautical and aerospace engineering intrinsic rotations around these axes are often called Euler angles, but this conflicts with existing usage elsewhere.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] The calculus behind them is similar to the Frenet–Serret formulas.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] Performing a rotation in an intrinsic reference frame is equivalent to right-multiplying its characteristic matrix (the matrix that has the vectors of the reference frame as columns) by the matrix of the rotation.
[src:autopilot-systems/aircraft-principal-axes] The first aircraft to demonstrate active control about all three axes was the Wright brothers' 1902 glider.
[src:autopilot-systems/attitude-and-heading-reference-system] An **attitude and heading reference system** (**AHRS**) consists of sensors on three axes that provide attitude information for aircraft, including roll, pitch, and yaw.
[src:autopilot-systems/attitude-and-heading-reference-system] These are sometimes referred to as **MARG** (Magnetic, Angular Rate, and Gravity) sensors and consist of either solid-state or microelectromechanical systems (MEMS) gyroscopes, accelerometers and magnetometers.
[src:autopilot-systems/attitude-and-heading-reference-system] They are designed to replace traditional mechanical gyroscopic flight instruments.
[src:autopilot-systems/attitude-and-heading-reference-system] The main difference between an Inertial measurement unit (IMU) and an AHRS is the addition of an on-board processing system in an AHRS, which provides attitude and heading information.
[src:autopilot-systems/attitude-and-heading-reference-system] This is in contrast to an IMU, which delivers sensor data to an additional device that computes attitude and heading.
[src:autopilot-systems/attitude-and-heading-reference-system] With sensor fusion, drift from the gyroscopes integration is compensated for by reference vectors, namely gravity, and the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:autopilot-systems/attitude-and-heading-reference-system] This results in a drift-free orientation, making an AHRS a more cost effective solution than conventional high-grade IMUs that only integrate gyroscopes and rely on a high bias stability of the gyroscopes.
[src:autopilot-systems/attitude-and-heading-reference-system] In addition to attitude determination an AHRS may also form part of an inertial navigation system.
[src:autopilot-systems/attitude-and-heading-reference-system] A form of non-linear estimation such as an Extended Kalman filter is typically used to compute the solution from these multiple sources.
[src:autopilot-systems/attitude-and-heading-reference-system] AHRS is reliable and is common in commercial and business aircraft.
[src:autopilot-systems/attitude-and-heading-reference-system] AHRS is typically integrated with electronic flight instrument systems (EFIS) which are the central part of glass cockpits, to form the primary flight display.
[src:autopilot-systems/attitude-and-heading-reference-system] AHRS can be combined with air data computers to form an Air data, attitude and heading reference system (ADAHRS), which provide additional information such as airspeed, altitude and outside air temperature.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] In aviation, **autoland** describes a system that fully automates the landing procedure of an aircraft's flight, with the flight crew supervising the process.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Such systems enable airliners to land in weather conditions that would otherwise be dangerous or impossible to operate in.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] A few general aviation aircraft have begun to be fitted with "emergency autoland" systems that can be activated by passengers, or by automated crew monitoring systems.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The emergency autoland systems are designed to complete an emergency landing at the nearest suitable airport, without any further human intervention, in the event that the flight crew is incapacitated.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Autoland systems were designed to make landing possible in visibility too poor to permit any form of visual landing, although they can be used at any level of visibility.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] They may also include automatic braking to a full stop once the aircraft is on the ground, in conjunction with the autobrake system, and sometimes auto deployment of spoilers and thrust reversers.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Autoland may be used for any suitably approved instrument landing system (ILS) or microwave landing system (MLS) approach, and is sometimes used to maintain currency of the aircraft and crew, as well as for its main purpose of assisting an aircraft landing in low visibility and/or bad weather.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Autoland requires the use of a radar altimeter to determine the aircraft's height above the ground very precisely so as to initiate the landing flare at the correct height (usually about 50 feet (15 m)).
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The localizer signal of the ILS may be used for lateral control even after touchdown until the autopilot is disengaged.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] For safety reasons, once autoland is engaged and the ILS signals have been acquired by the autoland system, it will proceed to landing without further intervention.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] It can be disengaged only by completely disconnecting the autopilot (this prevents accidental disengagement of the autoland system at a critical moment) or by initiating an automatic go-around.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] At least two and often three independent autopilot systems work in concert to carry out autoland, thus providing redundant protection against failures.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Most autoland systems can operate with a single autopilot in an emergency, but they are only certified when multiple autopilots are available.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The first aircraft to be certified to CAT III standards, on 28 December 1968, was the Sud Aviation Caravelle, followed by the Hawker-Siddeley HS.121 Trident in May 1972 (CAT IIIA) and to CAT IIIB during 1975.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The Trident had been certified to CAT II on 7 February 1968.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] IIIB landings, and a Ground Run Monitor (GRM) for measuring ground speed and distance travelled as an aid for estimating runway turn-off points and taxying.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Autoland capability has seen the most rapid adoption in areas and on aircraft that must frequently operate in very poor visibility.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Airports troubled by fog on a regular basis are prime candidates for Category III approaches, and including autoland capability on jet airliners helps reduce the likelihood that they will be forced to divert by bad weather.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Previously, autoland systems have been so expensive that they were rarely used on small aircraft.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] However, as display technology has developed, the addition of a head up display (HUD) allows for a trained pilot to manually fly the aircraft using guidance cues from the flight guidance system.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] This significantly reduces the cost of operating in very low visibility, and allows aircraft that are not equipped for automatic landings to make a manual landing safely at lower levels of look ahead visibility or runway visual range (RVR).
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] In 1989, Alaska Airlines was the first airline in the world to manually land a passenger-carrying jet (Boeing B727) in FAA Category III weather (dense fog) made possible with the head-up guidance system.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Commercial aviation autoland was initially developed in the United Kingdom, as a result of the frequent occurrence of very low visibility conditions in winter in Northwest Europe.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] These occur particularly when anticyclones are in place over Central Europe in November/December/January when temperatures are low, and radiation fog easily forms in relatively stable air.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The severity of this type of fog was exacerbated in the late 1940s and 1950s by the prevalence of carbon and other smoke particles in the air from coal burning heating and power generation.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Cities particularly affected included the main UK centers, and their airports such as London Heathrow, London Gatwick, Manchester, Birmingham and Glasgow, as well as European cities such as Amsterdam, Brussels, Paris, Zurich and Milan.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Visibility at these times could become as low as a few feet (hence the London fogs of movie fame) and, when combined with the soot, created lethal long-persistence smog.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] These conditions led to the passing of the UK's "Clean Air Act," which banned the burning of smoke-producing fuel.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] During the immediate post-war period, British European Airways (BEA) suffered a number of accidents during approach and landing in poor visibility, which caused it to focus on the problems of how pilots could land safely in such conditions.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] This led to the development of what is now widely understood as the "monitored approach" procedure.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] One pilot is assigned the task of accurate instrument flying while the other assesses the visual cues available at decision height, taking control to execute the landing once satisfied that the aircraft is in fact in the correct place and on a safe trajectory for a landing.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] However, associated with this "human factors" approach was a recognition that improved autopilots could play a major part in low-visibility landings.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The components of all landings are the same, involving navigation from a point at altitude en route to a point where the wheels are on the desired runway.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] This navigation is accomplished using information from either external, physical, visual cues, or from synthetic cues such as flight instruments.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] At all times, there must be sufficient total information to ensure that the aircraft's position and trajectory (vertical and horizontal) are correct.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The problem with low visibility operations is that the visual cues may be reduced to effectively zero, and hence there is an increased reliance on "synthetic" information.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The dilemma faced by BEA was to find a way to operate without cues, because this situation occurred on its network with far greater frequency than on that of any other airline.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] It was particularly prevalent at its home base, London Heathrow, which could effectively be closed for days at a time.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The United Kingdom government's aviation research facilities including the Blind Landing Experimental Unit (BLEU) set up during 1945/46 at RAF Martlesham Heath and RAF Woodbridge to research all the relevant factors.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] BEA's flight technical personnel were heavily involved in BLEU's activities in the development of Autoland for its Trident fleet from the late 1950s.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The work included analysis of fog structures, human perception, instrument design, and lighting cues amongst many others.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] After further accidents, this work also led to the development of aircraft operating minima in the form we know them today.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] In particular, it led to the requirement that a minimum visibility must be reported as available before the aircraft may commence an approach – a concept that had not existed previously.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The basic concept of a "target level of safety" (10^-7) and of the analysis of "fault trees" to determine probability of failure events stemmed from about this period.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The basic concept of autoland flows from the fact that an autopilot could be set up to track an artificial signal such as an Instrument Landing System (ILS) beam more accurately than a human pilot could – not least because of the inadequacies of the electro-mechanical flight instruments of the time.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] If the ILS beam could be tracked to a lower height then clearly the aircraft would be nearer to the runway when it reached the limit of ILS usability, and nearer to the runway less visibility would be required to see sufficient cues to confirm the aircraft position and trajectory.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] With an angular signal system such as ILS, as altitude decreases all tolerances must be decreased – in both the aircraft system and the input signal – to maintain the required degree of safety.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] This is because certain other factors – physical and physiological laws which govern for example the pilot's ability to make the aircraft respond – remain constant.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] For example, at 300 feet above the runway on a standard 3 degree approach the aircraft will be 6000 feet from the touchdown point, and at 100 feet it will be 2000 feet out.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] If a small course correction needs 10 seconds to be effected at 180 kts it will take 3000 ft.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] It will be possible if initiated at 300 feet of height, but not at 100 feet.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Consequently, only a smaller course correction can be tolerated at the lower height, and the system needs to be more accurate.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] This imposes a requirement for the ground-based, guidance element to conform to specific standards, as well as the airborne elements.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Thus, while an aircraft may be equipped with an autoland system, it will be totally unusable without the appropriate ground environment.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Similarly, it requires a crew trained in all aspects of the operation to recognize potential failures in both airborne and ground equipment, and to react appropriately, to be able to use the system in the circumstances for which it is intended.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Consequently, the low visibility operations categories (Cat I, Cat II and Cat III) apply to all 3 elements in the landing – the aircraft equipment, the ground environment, and the crew.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The result of all this is to create a spectrum of low visibility equipment, in which an aircraft's autoland autopilot is just one component.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The development of these systems proceeded by recognizing that although the ILS would be the source of the guidance, the ILS itself contains lateral and vertical elements that have rather different characteristics.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] In particular, the vertical element (glideslope) originates from the projected touchdown point of the approach, i.e., typically 1000 ft from the beginning of the runway, while the lateral element (localizer) originates from beyond the far end.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The transmitted glideslope therefore becomes irrelevant soon after the aircraft has reached the runway threshold, and in fact the aircraft has of course to enter its landing mode and reduce its vertical velocity quite a long time before it passes the glideslope transmitter.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The inaccuracies in the basic ILS could be seen in that it was suitable for use down to 200 ft. only (Cat I), and similarly no autopilot was suitable for or approved for use below this height.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The lateral guidance from the ILS localizer would, however, be usable right to the end of the landing roll, and hence is used to feed the rudder channel of the autopilot after touchdown.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] As aircraft approach the transmitter, its speed is obviously reducing and rudder effectiveness diminishes, compensating to some extent for the increased sensitivity of the transmitted signal.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] More significantly, however, it means the safety of the aircraft is still dependent on the ILS during rollout.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Furthermore, as it taxis off the runway and down any parallel taxiway, it itself acts a reflector and can interfere with the localizer signal.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] This means that it can affect the safety of any following aircraft still using the localizer.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] As a result, such aircraft cannot be allowed to rely on that signal until the first aircraft is well clear of the runway and the "Cat.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The result is that when these low visibility operations are taking place, operations on the ground affect operations in the air much more than in good visibility, when pilots can see what is happening.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] At very busy airports, this results in restrictions in movement which can in turn severely impact the airport's capacity.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] In short, very low visibility operations such as autoland can only be conducted when aircraft, crews, ground equipment and air and ground traffic control all comply with more stringent requirements than normal.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The first "commercial development" automatic landings (as opposed to pure experimentation) were achieved through realizing that the vertical and lateral paths had different rules.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Although the localizer signal would be present throughout the landing, the glide slope had to be disregarded before touchdown in any event.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] It was recognized that if the aircraft had arrived at decision height (200 ft) on a correct, stable approach path – a prerequisite for a safe landing – it would have momentum along that path.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] This "ballistic" phase would end at the height when it became necessary to increase pitch and reduce power to enter the landing flare.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The pitch change occurs over the runway in the 1000 horizontal feet between the threshold and the glide slope antenna, and so can be accurately triggered by radio altimeter.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Autoland was first developed in BLEU and Royal Air Force (RAF) aircraft such as the English Electric Canberra, Vickers Varsity and Avro Vulcan, and later for BEA's Trident fleet, which entered service in the early 1960s.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The Trident was a 3-engined jet built by de Havilland with a similar configuration to the Boeing 727, and was extremely sophisticated for its time.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] BEA had specified a "zero-visibility" capability for it to deal with the problems of its fog-prone network.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] It had an autopilot designed to provide the necessary redundancy to tolerate failures during autoland, and it was this design which had triple redundancy.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] This autopilot used three simultaneous processing channels each giving a physical output.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] This concept was later used on the Concorde.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Some BAC 1-11 aircraft used by BEA also had a similar system.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The earliest experimental autopilot-controlled landings in commercial service were not in fact full auto landings but were termed "auto-flare".
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] In this mode, the pilot controlled the roll and yaw axes manually while the autopilot controlled the "flare" or pitch.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] These were often done in passenger service as part of the development program.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The Trident's autopilot had separate engagement switches for the pitch and roll components, and although the normal autopilot disengagement was by means of a conventional control yoke thumb-button, it was also possible to disengage the roll channel while leaving the pitch channel engaged.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] In these operations, the pilot had acquired full visual reference, normally well above decision height, but instead of fully disengaging the autopilot with the thumb-button, called for the second officer to latch off the roll channel only.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The second officer then controlled the lateral flight path manually while monitoring the autopilot's continued control of the vertical flight path – ready to completely disengage it at the first sign of any deviation.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] While this sounds as if it may add a risk element, in practice it is of course no different in principle than a training pilot monitoring a trainee's handling during on-line training or qualification.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Having proven the reliability and accuracy of the autopilot's ability to safely flare the aircraft, the next elements were to add in similar control of the thrust.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] This was done by a radio altimeter signal which drove the autothrottle servos to a flight idle setting.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] As the accuracy and reliability of the ground based ILS localiser was increased on a step by step basis, it was permissible to leave the roll channel engaged longer and longer, until in fact the aircraft had ceased to be airborne, and a fully automatic landing had in fact been completed.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The first such landing in a BEA Trident was achieved at RAE Bedford (by then home of BLEU) in March 1964.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The first on a commercial flight with passengers aboard was achieved on flight BE 343 on 10 June 1965, with a Trident 1 G-ARPR, from Paris to Heathrow with Captains Eric Poole and Frank Ormonroyd.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Subsequently, autoland systems became available on a number of aircraft types but the primary customers were those mainly European airlines whose networks were severely affected by radiation fog.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Early autoland systems needed a relatively stable air mass and could not operate in conditions of turbulence and in particular gusty crosswinds.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] In North America, it was generally the case that reduced but not zero visibility was often associated with these conditions, and if the visibility really became almost zero in, for example, blowing snow or other precipitation then operations would be impossible for other reasons.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] As a result, neither airlines nor airports placed a high priority on operations in the lowest visibility.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The provision of the necessary ground equipment (ILS) and associated systems for Category 3 operations was almost non existent and the major manufacturers did not regard it as a basic necessity for new aircraft.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] In general, during the 1970s and 1980s, it was available if a customer wanted it, but at such a high price (due to being a reduced production run item) that few airlines could see a cost justification for it.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] This led to the absurd situation for British Airways that as the launch customer for the Boeing 757 to replace the Trident, the brand-new "advanced" aircraft had inferior all-weather operations capability compared to the fleet being broken up for scrap.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] It was pointed out that British Airways had 12 such runways on its domestic network alone, four of them at its main base at Heathrow.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] In the 1980s and 1990s, there was increasing pressure globally from customer airlines for at least some improvements in low visibility operations; both for flight regularity and from safety considerations.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] At the same time, it became evident that the requirement for a true zero-visibility operation (as originally envisaged in the ICAO Category definitions) had diminished, as clean-air laws had reduced the adverse effect of smoke adding to radiation fog in the worst affected areas.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Improved avionics meant that the technology became cheaper to implement, and manufacturers raised the standard of the "basic" autopilot accuracy and reliability.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The result was that, on the whole, the larger new airliners were now able to absorb the costs of at least Category 2 autoland systems into their basic configuration.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Simultaneously, pilot organizations globally were advocating the use of Head Up Display systems primarily from a safety viewpoint.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Many operators in non-sophisticated environments without many ILS equipped runways were also looking for improvements.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The net effect was pressure within the industry to find alternative ways to achieve low visibility operations, such as a "hybrid" system which used a relatively low reliability autoland system monitored by the pilots via a HUD.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Alaska Airlines was a leader in this approach and undertook a lot of development work with Flight Dynamics and Boeing in this respect.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] A major problem with this approach was that European authorities were very reluctant to certificate such schemes as they undermined the well-proven concepts of "pure" autoland systems.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] This impasse was broken when British Airways became involved as a potential customer for Bombardier's Regional Jet, which could not accommodate a full Cat 3 autoland system, but would be required to operate in those conditions.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The wheel turned full circle in December 2006 when London Heathrow was affected for a long period by dense fog.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] This airport was operating at maximum capacity in good conditions, and the imposition of low visibility procedures required to protect the localizer signal for autoland systems meant a major reduction in capacity from approximately 60 to 30 landings per hour.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Since most airlines operating into Heathrow already had autoland-equipped aircraft, and thus expected to operate as normal, massive delays occurred.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The worst affected airline was British Airways, as it was the largest operator at the airport.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Garmin Aviation started studying an emergency autoland feature in 2001 and launched the program in 2010 with more than 100 employees, investing around $20 million.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Flight tests began in 2014 with 329 test landings completed in a Cessna 400 Corvalis and another 300 landings in other aircraft.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The feature is activated by a guarded red button on Garmin G3000 avionics.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] It evaluates winds, weather and fuel reserves to select a suitable diversion airport and takes over the aircraft controls to land.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] In addition, it advises ATC of the feature's intentions and displays instructions to occupants.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] A Piper M600 single-engine turboprop aircraft began flight tests in early 2018 and completed more than 170 landings to seek pending FAA certification, which it achieved in 2020.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Providing access to more than 9,000 runways over 4,500 ft (1,400 m) in length, it is offered from 2020 for $170,000 including extra equipment.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] It was also certified for the single-engine Cirrus Vision SF50 jet that same year, landing on runways over 5,836 ft (1,779 m), the SOCATA-Daher TBM 900, and will eventually be certified on other aircraft.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] In June 2021, the Garmin Autoland system won the 2020 Collier Trophy, for "the greatest achievement in aeronautics or astronautics in America" during the preceding year.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The Autoland system, which automatically chose a suitable airport, flight plan, and descent from high altitude pattern, landed safely at Rocky Mountain Metropolitan Airport Broomfield, Colorado.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] During the event, the autoland subsystem tuned the radio to proper tower frequency, transmitted computer-enunciated voice radio messages including call sign, pilot incapacitation, aircraft position, and estimated time of arrival to the chosen airport.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] Updates were transmitted every few minutes to which ground emergency units and air traffic controllers prepared the airport and cleared approach airspace for the emergency aircraft.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The incident marked the first recorded instance of a fully navigated and planned, pilot-incapacitation autoland in U.S. general aviation history.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] A typical autoland system consists of an ILS (integrated glideslope receiver, localizer receiver, and perhaps GPS receiver as well) radio to receive the localizer and glideslope signals.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The output of this radio will be a deviation from center which is provided to the flight control computer; this computer controls the aircraft control surfaces to maintain the aircraft centered on the localizer and glideslope.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The flight control computer also controls the aircraft throttles to maintain the appropriate approach speed.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] At the appropriate height above the ground (as indicated by the radio altimeter) the flight control computer will retard the throttles and initiate a pitch-up maneuver.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The purpose of this "flare" is to reduce the energy of the aircraft, reducing lift and allowing it to settle onto the runway.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] For CAT IIIc, the flight control computer will continue to accept deviations from the localizer and use the rudder to maintain the aircraft on the localizer (which is aligned with the runway centerline).
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] On landing, the spoilers will deploy; these are surfaces on the top of the wing towards the trailing edge which cause airflow over the wing to become turbulent, destroying lift.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] At the same time the autobrake system will apply the brakes.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The anti-skid system will modulate brake pressure to keep all wheels turning.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] As the speed decreases, the rudder will lose effectiveness and the pilot will need to control the direction of the airplane using nose wheel steering, a system which typically is not connected to the flight control computer.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] From an avionics safety perspective, a CAT IIIc landing is the worst-case scenario for safety analysis because a failure of the automatic systems from flare through the roll-out could easily result in a "hard over" (where a control surface deflects fully in one direction).
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] This would happen so fast that the flight crew may not effectively respond.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] For this reason, autoland systems are designed to incorporate a high degree of redundancy so that a single failure of any part of the system can be tolerated (fail active) and a second failure can be detected – at which point the autoland system will turn itself off (uncouple, fail passive).
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] One way of accomplishing this is to have "three of everything." Three ILS receivers, three radio altimeters, three flight control computers, and three ways of controlling the flight surfaces.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The three flight control computers all work in parallel and are in constant cross communications, comparing their inputs (ILS receivers and radio altimeters) with those of the other two flight control computers.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] If there is a difference in inputs, then a computer can "vote out" the deviant input and will notify the other computers that (for instance) "RA1 is faulty." If the outputs don't match, a computer can declare itself as faulty and, if possible, take itself off line.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] When the pilot arms the system (prior to capture of either the localizer or glideslope) the flight control computers perform an extensive series of built-in tests.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] For a CAT III landing, all the sensors and all the flight computers must be in good health before the pilot receives an "AUTOLAND ARM" indication (generic indications that will vary depending on equipment supplier and aircraft manufacturer).
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] If part of the system is in error, then an indication such as "APPROACH ONLY" would be presented to inform the flight crew that a CAT III landing is not possible.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] If the system is properly in the ARM mode, when the ILS receiver detects the localizer, then the autoland system mode will change to "LOCALIZER CAPTURE".
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The flight control computer will turn the aircraft into the localizer and fly along the localizer.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] A typical approach will have the aircraft come in "below the glideslope" (vertical guidance) so the airplane will fly along the localizer (aligned to the runway centerline) until the glideslope is detected.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] At this point, the autoland mode will change to CAT III and the aircraft will be flown by the flight control computer along the localizer and glideslope beams.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] The antennas for these systems are not at the runway touch down point, with the localizer being some distance beyond the runway.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] At a predefined distance above the ground, the aircraft will initiate the flare maneuver, maintain the same heading, and settle onto the runway within the designated touch down zone.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] This is termed "fail-active." In this state the autoland system is "one fault away" from disengaging so the "AUTOLAND FAULT" indication should inform the flight crew to monitor the system behavior very carefully and be ready to take control immediately.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] At this time, the flight crew must immediately take control of the aircraft as the automatic systems have done the safe thing by taking themselves off line.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] During system design, the predicted reliability numbers for the individual equipment which makes up the entire autoland system (sensors, computers, controls, and so forth) are combined and an overall probability of failure is calculated.
[src:autopilot-systems/autoland] As the threat exists primarily during the flare through roll-out, this exposure time is used and the overall failure probability must be less than one in a million.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] An **autopilot** is a system used to control the path of an aircraft without requiring constant intervention by a human operator.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] The autopilot does not replace human operators, but it assists them allowing them to focus on broader aspects of operations (for example, monitoring the trajectory, weather and on-board systems).
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] When present, an autopilot is often used in conjunction with an autothrottle, a system for controlling the power delivered by the engines.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] In the early days of aviation, aircraft required the continuous attention of a pilot to fly safely.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] As aircraft range increased, allowing flights of many hours, the constant attention led to serious fatigue.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] An autopilot is designed to perform some of the pilot's tasks.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] The first gyroscopic autopilot for aircraft was developed by Sperry Corporation in 1912.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] The system connected a gyroscopic heading indicator and attitude indicator to hydraulically operated elevators and rudder.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] It permitted the aircraft to fly straight and level on a compass course without a pilot's attention, greatly reducing the pilot's workload.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Lawrence Sperry, the son of famous inventor Elmer Sperry, demonstrated it in 1914 at an aviation safety contest held in Paris.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Sperry demonstrated the credibility of the invention by flying the aircraft with his hands away from the controls and visible to onlookers.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Elmer Sperry Jr., the son of Lawrence Sperry, and Capt Shiras continued work on the same autopilot after the war, and in 1930, they tested a more compact and reliable autopilot which kept a U.S.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Army Air Corps aircraft on a true heading and altitude for three hours.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] In 1930, the Royal Aircraft Establishment in the United Kingdom developed an autopilot called a **pilots' assister** that used a pneumatically spun gyroscope to move the flight controls.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] The autopilot was further developed, to include, for example, improved control algorithms and hydraulic servomechanisms.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Adding more instruments, such as radio-navigation aids, made it possible to fly at night and in bad weather.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Air Force C-53 made a transatlantic flight, including takeoff and landing, completely under the control of an autopilot.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Bill Lear developed his F-5 automatic pilot, and automatic approach control system, and was awarded the Collier Trophy in 1949.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] In the early 1920s, the Standard Oil tanker *J.A.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Moffet* became the first ship to use an autopilot.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] The Piasecki HUP-2 Retriever was the first production helicopter with an autopilot.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] The lunar module digital autopilot of the Apollo program is an early example of a fully digital autopilot system in spacecraft.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Not all of the passenger aircraft flying today have an autopilot system.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Older and smaller general aviation aircraft especially are still hand-flown, and even small airliners with fewer than twenty seats may also be without an autopilot as they are used on short-duration flights with two pilots.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] The installation of autopilots in aircraft with more than twenty seats is generally made mandatory by international aviation regulations.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] There are three levels of control in autopilots for smaller aircraft.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Autopilots in modern complex aircraft are three-axis and generally divide a flight into taxi, takeoff, climb, cruise (level flight), descent, approach, and landing phases.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Autopilots that automate all of these flight phases except taxi and takeoff exist.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] An autopilot-controlled approach to landing on a runway and controlling the aircraft on rollout (i.e. keeping it on the centre of the runway) is known as an Autoland, where the autopilot utilizes an Instrument Landing System (ILS) Cat IIIc approach, which is used when the visibility is zero.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] These approaches are available at many major airports' runways today, especially at airports subject to adverse weather phenomena such as fog.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] The aircraft can typically stop on their own, but will require the disengagement of the autopilot in order to exit the runway and taxi to the gate.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] An autopilot is often an integral component of a Flight Management System.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Modern autopilots use computer software to control the aircraft.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] The software reads the aircraft's current position, and then controls a flight control system to guide the aircraft.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] In such a system, besides classic flight controls, many autopilots incorporate thrust control capabilities that can control throttles to optimize the airspeed.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] The autopilot in a modern large aircraft typically reads its position and the aircraft's attitude from an inertial guidance system.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Inertial guidance systems accumulate errors over time.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] They will incorporate error reduction systems such as the carousel system that rotates once a minute so that any errors are dissipated in different directions and have an overall nulling effect.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] This is due to physical properties within the system, be it mechanical or laser guided, that corrupt positional data.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] The disagreements between the two are resolved with digital signal processing, most often a six-dimensional Kalman filter.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] The six dimensions are usually roll, pitch, yaw, altitude, latitude, and longitude.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Aircraft may fly routes that have a required performance factor, therefore the amount of error or actual performance factor must be monitored in order to fly those particular routes.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] The longer the flight, the more error accumulates within the system.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Radio aids such as DME, DME updates, and GPS may be used to correct the aircraft position.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] An option midway between fully automated flight and manual flying is **Control Wheel Steering** (**CWS**).
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Although it is becoming less used as a stand-alone option in modern airliners, CWS is still a function on many aircraft today.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Generally, an autopilot that is CWS equipped has three positions: off, CWS, and CMD.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] In CMD (Command) mode the autopilot has full control of the aircraft, and receives its input from either the heading/altitude setting, radio and navaids, or the FMS (Flight Management System).
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] In CWS mode, the pilot controls the autopilot through inputs on the yoke or the stick.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] These inputs are translated to a specific heading and attitude, which the autopilot will then hold until instructed to do otherwise.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] This provides stability in pitch and roll.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Some aircraft employ a form of CWS even in manual mode, such as the MD-11 which uses a constant CWS in roll.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] In many ways, a modern Airbus fly-by-wire aircraft in Normal Law is always in CWS mode.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] The major difference is that in this system the limitations of the aircraft are guarded by the flight control computer, and the pilot cannot steer the aircraft past these limits.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] The hardware of an autopilot varies between implementations, but is generally designed with redundancy and reliability as foremost considerations.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] For example, the Rockwell Collins AFDS-770 Autopilot Flight Director System used on the Boeing 777 uses triplicated FCP-2002 microprocessors which have been formally verified and are fabricated in a radiation-resistant process.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Software and hardware in an autopilot are tightly controlled, and extensive test procedures are put in place.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Some autopilots also use design diversity.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] In this safety feature, critical software processes will not only run on separate computers, and possibly even using different architectures, but each computer will run software created by different engineering teams, often being programmed in different programming languages.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] It is generally considered unlikely that different engineering teams will make the same mistakes.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] As the software becomes more expensive and complex, design diversity is becoming less common because fewer engineering companies can afford it.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] The flight control computers on the Space Shuttle used this design: there were five computers, four of which redundantly ran identical software, and a fifth backup running software that was developed independently.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] The software on the fifth system provided only the basic functions needed to fly the Shuttle, further reducing any possible commonality with the software running on the four primary systems.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] A stability augmentation system (SAS) is another type of automatic flight control system; however, instead of maintaining the aircraft required altitude or flight path, the SAS will move the aircraft control surfaces to damp unacceptable motions.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] SAS automatically stabilizes the aircraft in one or more axes.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] The most common type of SAS is the yaw damper which is used to reduce the Dutch roll tendency of swept-wing aircraft.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Some yaw dampers are part of the autopilot system while others are stand-alone systems.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Yaw dampers use a sensor to detect how fast the aircraft is rotating (either a gyroscope or a pair of accelerometers), a computer/amplifier and an actuator.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] The sensor detects when the aircraft begins the yawing part of Dutch roll.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] A computer processes the signal from the sensor to determine the rudder deflection required to damp the motion.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] The computer tells the actuator to move the rudder in the opposite direction to the motion since the rudder has to oppose the motion to reduce it.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] The Dutch roll is damped and the aircraft becomes stable about the yaw axis.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Because Dutch roll is an instability that is inherent in all swept-wing aircraft, most swept-wing aircraft need some sort of yaw damper.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] There are two types of yaw damper: the series yaw damper and the parallel yaw damper.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] The actuator of a parallel yaw damper will move the rudder independently of the pilot's rudder pedals while the actuator of a series yaw damper is clutched to the rudder control quadrant, and will result in pedal movement when the rudder moves.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Some aircraft have stability augmentation systems that will stabilize the aircraft in more than a single axis.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] The Boeing B-52, for example, requires both pitch and yaw SAS in order to provide a stable bombing platform.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Many helicopters have pitch, roll and yaw SAS systems.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Pitch and roll SAS systems operate much the same way as the yaw damper described above; however, instead of damping Dutch roll, they will damp pitch and roll oscillations to improve the overall stability of the aircraft.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Instrument-aided landings are defined in categories by the International Civil Aviation Organization, or ICAO.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] These are dependent upon the required visibility level and the degree to which the landing can be conducted automatically without input by the pilot.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Fail-passive autopilot: in case of failure, the aircraft stays in a controllable position and the pilot can take control of it to go around or finish landing.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Fail-operational autopilot: in case of a failure below alert height, the approach, flare and landing can still be completed automatically.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] It is usually a triple-channel system or dual-dual system.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] In radio-controlled modelling, and especially RC aircraft and helicopters, an autopilot is usually a set of extra hardware and software that deals with pre-programming the model's flight.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] A flight director (FD) is a flight instrument that is overlaid on the attitude indicator that shows the pilot of an aircraft the attitude required to execute the desired flight path.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] While the flight director is separate from the autopilot, they are closely linked.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] With a flight plan programmed into the flight computer, the flight director will command rolls when turns are required.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] Without a flight director, the autopilot is limited to more basic modes, such as maintaining an altitude or a heading, or turning on to a new heading when commanded by the pilot.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] When the autopilot and flight director are used together, more complex autopilot modes are possible.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] The autopilot can follow flight director commands, thus following the flight plan route without pilot intervention.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] An autopilot system is sometimes colloquially referred to as *"George"* (e.g.
[src:autopilot-systems/autopilot] *"we'll let George fly for a while"; "George is flying the plane now".*).
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] To do this, a **controller** with the requisite corrective behavior is required.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] This controller monitors the controlled process variable (PV), and compares it with the reference or set point (SP).
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] The difference between actual and desired value of the process variable, called the *error* signal, or SP-PV error, is applied as feedback to generate a control action to bring the controlled process variable to the same value as the set point.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Other aspects which are also studied are controllability and observability.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Control theory is used in control system engineering to design automation that have revolutionized manufacturing, aircraft, communications and other industries, and created new fields such as robotics.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Extensive use is usually made of a diagrammatic style known as the block diagram.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] In it the transfer function, also known as the system function or network function, is a mathematical model of the relation between the input and output based on the differential equations describing the system.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Control theory dates from the 19th century, when the theoretical basis for the operation of governors was first described by James Clerk Maxwell.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Control theory was further advanced by Edward Routh in 1874, Charles Sturm and in 1895, Adolf Hurwitz, who all contributed to the establishment of control stability criteria; and from 1922 onwards, the development of PID control theory by Nicolas Minorsky.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Although the most direct application of mathematical control theory is its use in control systems engineering (dealing with process control systems for robotics and industry), control theory is routinely applied to problems both the natural and behavioral sciences.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] As the general theory of feedback systems, control theory is useful wherever feedback occurs, making it important to fields like economics, operations research, and the life sciences.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Although control systems of various types date back to antiquity, a more formal analysis of the field began with a dynamics analysis of the centrifugal governor, conducted by the physicist James Clerk Maxwell in 1868, entitled *On Governors*.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] A centrifugal governor was already used to regulate the velocity of windmills.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Maxwell described and analyzed the phenomenon of self-oscillation, in which lags in the system may lead to overcompensation and unstable behavior.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] This generated a flurry of interest in the topic, during which Maxwell's classmate, Edward John Routh, abstracted Maxwell's results for the general class of linear systems.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Independently, Adolf Hurwitz analyzed system stability using differential equations in 1877, resulting in what is now known as the Routh–Hurwitz theorem.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] A notable application of dynamic control was in the area of crewed flight.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] The Wright brothers made their first successful test flights on December 17, 1903, and were distinguished by their ability to control their flights for substantial periods (more so than the ability to produce lift from an airfoil, which was known).
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Continuous, reliable control of the airplane was necessary for flights lasting longer than a few seconds.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] By World War II, control theory was becoming an important area of research.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Irmgard Flügge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic control systems, and applied the bang-bang principle to the development of automatic flight control equipment for aircraft.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Other areas of application for discontinuous controls included fire-control systems, guidance systems and electronics.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Sometimes, mechanical methods are used to improve the stability of systems.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] For example, ship stabilizers are fins mounted beneath the waterline and emerging laterally.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] In contemporary vessels, they may be gyroscopically controlled active fins, which have the capacity to change their angle of attack to counteract roll caused by wind or waves acting on the ship.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] The Space Race also depended on accurate spacecraft control, and control theory has also seen an increasing use in fields such as economics and artificial intelligence.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Here, one might say that the goal is to find an internal model that obeys the good regulator theorem.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] So, for example, in economics, the more accurately a (stock or commodities) trading model represents the actions of the market, the more easily it can control that market (and extract "useful work" (profits) from it).
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] These last two examples take the narrow historical interpretation of control theory as a set of differential equations modeling and regulating kinetic motion, and broaden it into a vast generalization of a regulator interacting with a plant.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Fundamentally, there are two types of control loop: *open-loop control* (feedforward), and *closed-loop control* (feedback).
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] A closed-loop controller or feedback controller is a control loop which incorporates feedback, in contrast to an *open-loop controller* or *non-feedback controller*.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] A closed-loop controller uses feedback to control states or outputs of a dynamical system.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] In the case of linear feedback systems, a control loop including sensors, control algorithms, and actuators is arranged in an attempt to regulate a variable at a setpoint (SP).
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] An everyday example is the cruise control on a road vehicle; where external influences such as hills would cause speed changes, and the driver has the ability to alter the desired set speed.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] The PID algorithm in the controller restores the actual speed to the desired speed in an optimum way, with minimal delay or overshoot, by controlling the power output of the vehicle's engine.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Control systems that include some sensing of the results they are trying to achieve are making use of feedback and can adapt to varying circumstances to some extent.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Open-loop control systems do not make use of feedback, and run only in pre-arranged ways.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] In some systems, closed-loop and open-loop control are used simultaneously.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] In such systems, the open-loop control is termed *feedforward* and serves to further improve reference tracking performance.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] A common closed-loop controller architecture is the PID controller.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] In contrast to the frequency-domain analysis of the classical control theory, modern control theory utilizes the time-domain state space representation, a mathematical model of a physical system as a set of input, output and state variables related by first-order differential equations.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] To abstract from the number of inputs, outputs, and states, the variables are expressed as vectors and the differential and algebraic equations are written in matrix form (the latter only being possible when the dynamical system is linear).
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] The state space representation (also known as the "time-domain approach") provides a convenient and compact way to model and analyze systems with multiple inputs and outputs.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] With inputs and outputs, we would otherwise have to write down Laplace transforms to encode all the information about a system.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Unlike the frequency domain approach, the use of the state-space representation is not limited to systems with linear components and zero initial conditions.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] "State space" refers to the space whose axes are the state variables.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] The state of the system can be represented as a point within that space.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Control systems can be divided into different categories depending on the number of inputs and outputs.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] The scope of classical control theory is limited to single-input and single-output (SISO) system design, except when analyzing for disturbance rejection using a second input.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] The system analysis is carried out in the time domain using differential equations, in the complex-s domain with the Laplace transform, or in the frequency domain by transforming from the complex-s domain.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Many systems may be assumed to have a second order and single variable system response in the time domain.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] A controller designed using classical theory often requires on-site tuning due to incorrect design approximations.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Yet, due to the easier physical implementation of classical controller designs as compared to systems designed using modern control theory, these controllers are preferred in most industrial applications.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] The most common controllers designed using classical control theory are PID controllers.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] A less common implementation may include either or both a Lead or Lag filter.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] The ultimate end goal is to meet requirements typically provided in the time-domain called the step response, or at times in the frequency domain called the open-loop response.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] The step response characteristics applied in a specification are typically percent overshoot, settling time, etc.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] The open-loop response characteristics applied in a specification are typically Gain and Phase margin and bandwidth.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] These characteristics may be evaluated through simulation including a dynamic model of the system under control coupled with the compensation model.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Modern control theory is carried out in the state space, and can deal with multiple-input and multiple-output (MIMO) systems.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] This overcomes the limitations of classical control theory in more sophisticated design problems, such as fighter aircraft control, with the limitation that no frequency domain analysis is possible.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] In modern design, a system is represented to the greatest advantage as a set of decoupled first order differential equations defined using state variables.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Nonlinear, multivariable, adaptive and robust control theories come under this division.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Being fairly new, modern control theory has many areas yet to be explored.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Kálmán and Aleksandr Lyapunov are well known among the people who have shaped modern control theory.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] The *stability* of a general dynamical system with no input can be described with Lyapunov stability criteria.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] For simplicity, the following descriptions focus on continuous-time and discrete-time **linear systems**.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Mathematically, this means that for a causal linear system to be stable all of the poles of its transfer function must have negative-real values, i.e. the real part of each pole must be less than zero.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] The difference between the two cases is simply due to the traditional method of plotting continuous time versus discrete time transfer functions.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] The continuous Laplace transform is in Cartesian coordinates where the x axis is the real axis and the discrete Z-transform is in circular coordinates where the $\rho$ axis is the real axis.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] When the appropriate conditions above are satisfied a system is said to be asymptotically stable; the variables of an asymptotically stable control system always decrease from their initial value and do not show permanent oscillations.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Permanent oscillations occur when a pole has a real part exactly equal to zero (in the continuous time case) or a modulus equal to one (in the discrete time case).
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] If a simply stable system response neither decays nor grows over time, and has no oscillations, it is marginally stable; in this case the system transfer function has non-repeated poles at the complex plane origin (i.e. their real and complex component is zero in the continuous time case).
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Oscillations are present when poles with real part equal to zero have an imaginary part not equal to zero.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] which has a pole in $z=0.5$ (zero imaginary part).
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] This system is BIBO (asymptotically) stable since the pole is *inside* the unit circle.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] which has a pole at $z=1.5$ and is not BIBO stable since the pole has a modulus strictly greater than one.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Numerous tools exist for the analysis of the poles of a system.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] These include graphical systems like the root locus, Bode plots or the Nyquist plots.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Mechanical changes can make equipment (and control systems) more stable.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Sailors add ballast to improve the stability of ships.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Cruise ships use antiroll fins that extend transversely from the side of the ship for perhaps 30 feet (10 m) and are continuously rotated about their axes to develop forces that oppose the roll.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Controllability and observability are main issues in the analysis of a system before deciding the best control strategy to be applied, or whether it is even possible to control or stabilize the system.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Controllability is related to the possibility of forcing the system into a particular state by using an appropriate control signal.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] If a state is not controllable, then no signal will ever be able to control the state.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] If a state is not controllable, but its dynamics are stable, then the state is termed *stabilizable*.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Observability instead is related to the possibility of *observing*, through output measurements, the state of a system.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] If a state is not observable, the controller will never be able to determine the behavior of an unobservable state and hence cannot use it to stabilize the system.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] However, similar to the stabilizability condition above, if a state cannot be observed it might still be detectable.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] From a geometrical point of view, looking at the states of each variable of the system to be controlled, every "bad" state of these variables must be controllable and observable to ensure a good behavior in the closed-loop system.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] That is, if one of the eigenvalues of the system is not both controllable and observable, this part of the dynamics will remain untouched in the closed-loop system.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] If such an eigenvalue is not stable, the dynamics of this eigenvalue will be present in the closed-loop system which therefore will be unstable.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Unobservable poles are not present in the transfer function realization of a state-space representation, which is why sometimes the latter is preferred in dynamical systems analysis.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Solutions to problems of an uncontrollable or unobservable system include adding actuators and sensors.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Several different control strategies have been devised in the past years.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] These vary from extremely general ones (PID controller), to others devoted to very particular classes of systems (especially robotics or aircraft cruise control).
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] A control problem can have several specifications.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Stability, of course, is always present.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] The controller must ensure that the closed-loop system is stable, regardless of the open-loop stability.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] A poor choice of controller can even worsen the stability of the open-loop system, which must normally be avoided.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Sometimes it would be desired to obtain particular dynamics in the closed loop: i.e. that the poles have $Re[\lambda ]<-{\overline {\lambda }}$ , where ${\overline {\lambda }}$ is a fixed value strictly greater than zero, instead of simply asking that $Re[\lambda ]<0$ .
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Another typical specification is the rejection of a step disturbance; including an integrator in the open-loop chain (i.e. directly before the system under control) easily achieves this.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Other classes of disturbances need different types of sub-systems to be included.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Other "classical" control theory specifications regard the time-response of the closed-loop system.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] These include the rise time (the time needed by the control system to reach the desired value after a perturbation), peak overshoot (the highest value reached by the response before reaching the desired value) and others (settling time, quarter-decay).
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Frequency domain specifications are usually related to robustness (see after).
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Modern performance assessments use some variation of integrated tracking error (IAE, ISA, CQI).
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] A control system must always have some robustness property.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] A robust controller is such that its properties do not change much if applied to a system slightly different from the mathematical one used for its synthesis.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] This requirement is important, as no real physical system truly behaves like the series of differential equations used to represent it mathematically.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Typically a simpler mathematical model is chosen in order to simplify calculations, otherwise, the true system dynamics can be so complicated that a complete model is impossible.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] The process of determining the equations that govern the model's dynamics is called system identification.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] This can be done off-line: for example, executing a series of measures from which to calculate an approximated mathematical model, typically its transfer function or matrix.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Such identification from the output, however, cannot take account of unobservable dynamics.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Sometimes the model is built directly starting from known physical equations, for example, in the case of a mass-spring-damper system we know that $m{\ddot {x}}(t)=-Kx(t)-\mathrm {B} {\dot {x}}(t)$ .
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Some advanced control techniques include an "on-line" identification process (see later).
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] The parameters of the model are calculated ("identified") while the controller itself is running.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] In this way, if a drastic variation of the parameters ensues, for example, if the robot's arm releases a weight, the controller will adjust itself consequently in order to ensure the correct performance.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Analysis of the robustness of a SISO (single input single output) control system can be performed in the frequency domain, considering the system's transfer function and using Nyquist and Bode diagrams.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Topics include gain and phase margin and amplitude margin.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] For MIMO (multi-input multi output) and, in general, more complicated control systems, one must consider the theoretical results devised for each control technique (see next section).
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] I.e., if particular robustness qualities are needed, the engineer must shift their attention to a control technique by including these qualities in its properties.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] A particular robustness issue is the requirement for a control system to perform properly in the presence of input and state constraints.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] In the physical world every signal is limited.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] It could happen that a controller will send control signals that cannot be followed by the physical system, for example, trying to rotate a valve at excessive speed.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] This can produce undesired behavior of the closed-loop system, or even damage or break actuators or other subsystems.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Specific control techniques are available to solve the problem: model predictive control (see later), and anti-wind up systems.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] The latter consists of an additional control block that ensures that the control signal never exceeds a given threshold.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] For MIMO systems, pole placement can be performed mathematically using a state space representation of the open-loop system and calculating a feedback matrix assigning poles in the desired positions.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] In complicated systems this can require computer-assisted calculation capabilities, and cannot always ensure robustness.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Furthermore, all system states are not in general measured and so observers must be included and incorporated in pole placement design.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Processes in industries like robotics and the aerospace industry typically have strong nonlinear dynamics.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] In control theory it is sometimes possible to linearize such classes of systems and apply linear techniques, but in many cases it can be necessary to devise from scratch theories permitting control of nonlinear systems.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] These, e.g., feedback linearization, backstepping, sliding mode control, trajectory linearization control normally take advantage of results based on Lyapunov's theory.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Differential geometry has been widely used as a tool for generalizing well-known linear control concepts to the nonlinear case, as well as showing the subtleties that make it a more challenging problem.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Control theory has also been used to decipher the neural mechanism that directs cognitive states.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] When the system is controlled by multiple controllers, the problem is one of decentralized control.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Decentralization is helpful in many ways, for instance, it helps control systems to operate over a larger geographical area.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] The agents in decentralized control systems can interact using communication channels and coordinate their actions.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] A stochastic control problem is one in which the evolution of the state variables is subjected to random shocks from outside the system.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] A deterministic control problem is not subject to external random shocks.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Every control system must guarantee first the stability of the closed-loop behavior.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] For linear systems, this can be obtained by directly placing the poles.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] Nonlinear control systems use specific theories (normally based on Aleksandr Lyapunov's Theory) to ensure stability without regard to the inner dynamics of the system.
[src:autopilot-systems/control-theory] The possibility to fulfill different specifications varies from the model considered and the control strategy chosen.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] In mechanical and control engineering, a **servomechanism** (also called **servo system**, or simply **servo**) is a control system for the position and its time derivatives, such as velocity, of a mechanical system.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] It often includes a servomotor, and uses closed-loop control to reduce steady-state error and improve dynamic response.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] In closed-loop control, error-sensing negative feedback is used to correct the action of the mechanism.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] In displacement-controlled applications, it usually includes a built-in encoder or other position feedback mechanism to ensure the output is achieving the desired effect.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] Following a specified motion trajectory is called **servoing**, where "servo" is used as a verb.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] The *servo* prefix originates from the Latin word *servus* meaning 'slave'.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] The term correctly applies only to systems where the feedback or error-correction signals help control mechanical position, speed, attitude or any other measurable variables.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] For example, an automotive power window control is not a servomechanism, as there is no automatic feedback that controls position—the operator does this by observation.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] By contrast a car's cruise control uses closed-loop feedback, which classifies it as a servomechanism.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] A common type of servo provides *position control*.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] Commonly, servos are electric, hydraulic, or pneumatic.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] They operate on the principle of negative feedback, where the control input is compared to the actual position of the mechanical system as measured by some type of transducer at the output.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] Any positive or negative difference between the actual and wanted values (an "**error signal**") is amplified (and converted) and used to drive the system's motor in the direction necessary to reduce or eliminate the error, e.g. through an H-bridge controller.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] This procedure is one widely used application of control theory.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] Typical servos can give a rotary (angular) or linear output.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] Speed control via a governor is another type of servomechanism.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] The steam engine uses mechanical governors; another early application was to govern the speed of water wheels.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] Prior to World War II the constant speed propeller was developed to control engine speed for maneuvering aircraft.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] Fuel controls for gas turbine engines employ either hydromechanical or electronic governing.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] Positioning servomechanisms were first used in military fire-control and marine navigation equipment.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] Today servomechanisms are used in automatic machine tools, satellite-tracking antennas, remote control airplanes, automatic navigation systems on boats and planes, and antiaircraft-gun control systems.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] Other examples are fly-by-wire systems in aircraft which use servos to actuate the aircraft's control surfaces, and radio-controlled models which use RC servos for the same purpose.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] Many autofocus cameras also use a servomechanism to accurately move the lens.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] A hard disk drive has a magnetic servo system with sub-micrometer positioning accuracy.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] In industrial machines, servos are used to perform complex motion, in many applications.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] A *servomotor* is a specific type of motor that is combined with a rotary encoder or a potentiometer to form a servomechanism.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] This assembly may in turn form part of another servomechanism.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] A potentiometer provides a simple analog signal to indicate position, while an encoder provides position and usually speed feedback, which by the use of a PID controller allow more precise control of position and thus faster achievement of a stable position (for a given motor power).
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] Potentiometers are subject to drift when the temperature changes whereas encoders are more stable and accurate.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] Servomotors are used for both high-end and low-end applications.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] On the high end are precision industrial components that use a rotary encoder.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] On the low end are inexpensive radio control servos (RC servos) used in radio-controlled models which use a free-running motor and a simple potentiometer position sensor with an embedded controller.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] The term *servomotor* generally refers to a high-end industrial component while the term *servo* is most often used to describe the inexpensive devices that employ a potentiometer.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] Stepper motors are not considered to be servomotors, although they too are used to construct larger servomechanisms.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] Stepper motors have inherent angular positioning, owing to their construction, and this is generally used in an open-loop manner without feedback.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] They are generally used for medium-precision applications.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] RC servos are used to provide actuation for various mechanical systems such as the steering of a car, the control surfaces on a plane, or the rudder of a boat.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] Due to their affordability, reliability, and simplicity of control by microprocessors, they are often used in small-scale robotics applications.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] A standard RC receiver (or a microcontroller) sends pulse-width modulation (PWM) signals to the servo.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] The electronics inside the servo translate the width of the pulse into a position.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] When the servo is commanded to rotate, the motor is powered until the potentiometer reaches the value corresponding to the commanded position.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] James Watt's steam engine governor is generally considered the first powered feedback system.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] The windmill fantail is an earlier example of automatic control, but since it does not have an amplifier or gain, it is not usually considered a servomechanism.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] The first feedback position control device was the ship steering engine, used to position the rudder of large ships based on the position of the ship's wheel.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] His patented design was used on the SS Great Eastern in 1866.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] Joseph Farcot may deserve equal credit for the feedback concept, with several patents between 1862 and 1868.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] The telemotor was invented around 1872 by Andrew Betts Brown, allowing elaborate mechanisms between the control room and the engine to be greatly simplified.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] Steam steering engines had the characteristics of a modern servomechanism: an input, an output, an error signal, and a means for amplifying the error signal used for negative feedback to drive the error towards zero.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] The Ragonnet power reverse mechanism was a general purpose air or steam-powered servo amplifier for linear motion patented in 1909.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] Electrical servomechanisms were used as early as 1888 in Elisha Gray's Telautograph.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] Electrical servomechanisms require a power amplifier.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] World War II saw the development of electrical fire-control servomechanisms, using an amplidyne as the power amplifier.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] Vacuum tube amplifiers were used in the UNISERVO tape drive for the UNIVAC I computer.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] The Royal Navy began experimenting with Remote Power Control (RPC) on HMS Champion in 1928 and began using RPC to control searchlights in the early 1930s.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] During WW2 RPC was used to control gun mounts and gun directors.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] Modern servomechanisms use solid state power amplifiers, usually built from MOSFET or thyristor devices.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] The origin of the word is believed to come from the French "*Le Servomoteur*" or the slavemotor, first used by J.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] Farcot in 1868 to describe hydraulic and steam engines for use in ship steering.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] The simplest kind of servos use bang–bang control.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] More complex control systems use proportional control, PID control, and state space control, which are studied in modern control theory.
[src:autopilot-systems/servomechanism] The servo bandwidth indicates the capability of the servo to follow rapid changes in the commanded input.
[src:autopilot-systems/yaw-damper] A **yaw damper** (sometimes referred to as a **stability augmentation system**) is a system used to reduce (or damp) the undesirable tendency of an aircraft to oscillate in a repetitive rolling and yawing motion, a phenomenon known as the Dutch roll.
[src:autopilot-systems/yaw-damper] A large number of modern aircraft, both jet-powered and propeller-driven, have been furnished with such systems.
[src:autopilot-systems/yaw-damper] The use of a yaw damper provides superior ride quality by automatically preventing uncomfortable yawing and rolling oscillations and reduces pilot workload.
[src:autopilot-systems/yaw-damper] On some aircraft, it is mandatory for the yaw damper to be operational at all times during flight above a specified altitude; several airliners were deemed to be unsafe to fly without an active yaw damper.
[src:autopilot-systems/yaw-damper] The yaw damper system consists of accelerometers and sensors that monitor the aircraft rate of yaw; these are electronically connected to a flight computer that processes the signals and automatically controls actuators connected to the rudder.
[src:autopilot-systems/yaw-damper] In effect, these actions are akin to movements of the rudder pedals by the pilot, except that these are automated.
[src:autopilot-systems/yaw-damper] The rudder motions produced by the yaw damper act to calm the aircraft, assisting the flight crew in maintaining stable flight.
[src:autopilot-systems/yaw-damper] The purpose of the yaw damper is to make an aircraft easier to fly by eliminating the necessity for the pilot to act against such tendencies.
[src:autopilot-systems/yaw-damper] A yaw damper may remove the necessity for a pilot to make any contact with the rudder pedals during turns on a range of aircraft, including jet-powered ones.
[src:autopilot-systems/yaw-damper] Some aircraft, such as the Boeing 727 and Vickers VC10 airliners, are fitted with multiple yaw damper systems due to their operation having been deemed critical to flight safety.
[src:autopilot-systems/yaw-damper] Despite what may be implied by its name, the yaw damper does not inhibit or reduce intentional (e.g. commanded by the pilot) yaw, as this would interfere with conventional turns and other common maneuvers that an aircraft would be expected to perform.
[src:autopilot-systems/yaw-damper] Rather, the system is intended to counteract incidental and undirected yawing motions, which can be characterised as skids or slips.
[src:autopilot-systems/yaw-damper] On a single-engine aircraft, the system is particularly useful at addressing the tendency to 'fishtail', smoothing out the left–right movements of the vertical stabilizer (fin), increasing ride comfort.
[src:autopilot-systems/yaw-damper] The yaw damper is typically disengaged at ground level and turned on shortly after takeoff; an active yaw damper during the takeoff run could potentially mask serious issues such as engine failure.
[src:autopilot-systems/yaw-damper] Equally, the system is commonly disengaged prior to landing, as it could inhibit the control authority to the pilot at the critical moment of touchdown.
[src:autopilot-systems/yaw-damper] On several modern aircraft that are outfitted with a yaw damper, these systems become engaged automatically once the aircraft has surpassed a set altitude (e.g.
[src:autopilot-systems/yaw-damper] 200 feet); older aircraft typically have this function manually selected by the flight crew.
[src:autopilot-systems/yaw-damper] Pilots who are used to flying aircraft with yaw dampers need to be particularly aware when flying aircraft that lack them.
[src:autopilot-systems/yaw-damper] It has become common for such systems to be interfaced with other elements of an aircraft's avionics, enabling it to work with other functions such as the autopilot.
[src:autopilot-systems/yaw-damper] Yaw damping can be readily simulated by software packages, such as Matlab.
